        <!-- Hero Section -->
        <section id="welcome" class="min-h-screen flex items-center justify-center text-center px-4">
            <div class="max-w-4xl">
                <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-6xl lg:text-7xl font-bold text-white leading-tight">TECHNO DRUM MACHINE</h1>
                <h2 class="text-4xl md:text-6xl lg:text-7xl hero-subtitle uppercase text-gray-300">Theory Course</h2>
                <p class="mt-8 max-w-2xl mx-auto text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
                    This course explores the theoretical underpinnings and practical considerations of crafting compelling techno drum patterns for live performance, treating the drum machine not as a simple sequencer, but as a complete performance instrument.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Course Content Wrapper -->
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-8">

            <!-- Module 1 -->
            <section id="module1" class="py-16 md:py-24">
                <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-12">Module 1: The Foundational Elements</h2>
                
                <div class="space-y-12">
                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-xl text-white mb-4">The Crucial Role of the Kick Drum</h3>
                        <p class="text-gray-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">The kick drum is the soul of techno, its unwavering heartbeat. It is the primary anchor for both the performer and the audience.</p>
                        <ul class="list-disc list-outside space-y-3 text-gray-300 pl-5">
                            <li><strong>The Four-on-the-Floor:</strong> This pattern, typically at tempos from 120-140 BPM, is more than a simple pulse. It's a psychoacoustic constant that induces a trance-like state. The choice of kick sound is paramount: a short, punchy kick with a tight decay creates space, while a long, boomy kick can become a tonal element.</li>
                            <li><strong>Driving Rhythms:</strong> A double kick, often placed on the last eighth or sixteenth note of a phrase, acts as a rhythmic "turnaround," propelling energy into the next bar and creating anticipation.</li>
                            <li><strong>Nuance and Velocity:</strong> Even with a 4/4 pattern, subtle velocity variations are key. Setting kicks on beats 1 and 3 to a slightly higher velocity than 2 and 4 creates a subtle "push-pull" dynamic.</li>
                            <li><strong>Metrical Stability and Tuning:</strong> The kick is the metrical anchor. Tuning it to the root note of your track (or its fifth) can create a powerful sense of harmonic cohesion.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-xl text-white mb-4">Defining the Groove with Hi-Hats and Claps</h3>
                        <p class="text-gray-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">If the kick is the foundation, the hi-hats and claps are the architecture built upon it, defining the energy and character.</p>
                        <ul class="list-disc list-outside space-y-3 text-gray-300 pl-5">
                            <li><strong>Hi-Hats:</strong> The interplay between open and closed hi-hats is a primary tool for tension and release. Program a 16-step pattern with velocity variations to create a dynamic, shimmering texture.</li>
                            <li><strong>Claps:</strong> The classic placement on beats 2 and 4 provides the backbeat. The "snappy" feel achieved by shifting the clap a few milliseconds *before* the kick works by creating a rhythmic "flam," making the subsequent kick feel more impactful.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-xl text-white mb-4">Adding Layers and Intricacy with Other Percussion</h3>
                        <p class="text-gray-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">These elements are the sonic details that reward deep listening and give a track its unique identity.</p>
                        <ul class="list-disc list-outside space-y-3 text-gray-300 pl-5">
                            <li><strong>Snares:</strong> Can be used to create complex counter-rhythms with lower velocity "ghost notes" to add a funky, rolling quality.</li>
                            <li><strong>Toms & Percussion:</strong> A tuned tom pattern can become a central hypnotic element. Use other sounds sparsely for rhythmic punctuation.</li>
                            <li><strong>Rim Shots:</strong> Perfect for creating complex, polyrhythmic patterns, like a continuous 3/16 pattern against a 4/4 kick.</li>
                            <li><strong>Crash Cymbals:</strong> Use them to signify major structural changes. Experiment with reverse cymbals for tension.</li>
                            <li><strong>Ride Cymbals:</strong> The character of the ride often defines a track's subgenre. A bright, "pingy" ride lends urgency, while a darker, "washy" ride adds atmosphere.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- Module 2 -->
            <section id="module2" class="py-16 md:py-24">
                <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-12">Module 2: Rhythmic & Metrical Foundations</h2>
                <div class="space-y-12">
                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-xl text-white mb-4">The Art of Repetition and Loop-Based Structures</h3>
                        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">The 4/4 loop is a canvas, not a cage. Its hypnotic power lies in the fact that, over time, the human brain seeks out new patterns within the static information. This "listener participation" is a core tenet of techno, where micro-timing adjustments and subtle sonic changes become major events.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-xl text-white mb-4">Understanding Metrical Dissonance and Ambiguity</h3>
                        <p class="text-gray-400 leading-relaxed mb-4">This is the art of creating tension through conflicting rhythms.</p>
                        <ul class="list-disc list-outside space-y-3 text-gray-300 pl-5">
                            <li><strong>Metrical Dissonance:</strong> Imagine a 4/4 kick drum pattern. Now, layer a percussion sound that plays a 3-beat pattern over the same duration (a polymeter). The patterns will only align once every 12 beats, creating an evolving rhythmic phrase.</li>
                            <li><strong>Rhythmic Ambiguity:</strong> This dissonance forces the listener's brain to choose which rhythm to focus on, making the listening experience active.</li>
                            <li><strong>Immediate Effect:</strong> In techno, this is a tool for real-time performance. Bringing in a dissonant loop for 16 bars can dramatically increase intensity before snapping back to a consonant groove.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-xl text-white mb-4">The Significance of Layering and Textural Equality</h3>
                        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">A layered approach is fundamental, creating a "democracy of sound." Unlike vocally-driven pop music, no single element in techno is necessarily the "star." The kick, bassline, hats, and synth can all be perceived as the lead element at different times.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-xl text-white mb-4">Exploring Asymmetrical Rhythms</h3>
                        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">While techno is built on a 4/4 foundation, asymmetrical patterns provide the "funk." The classic 3+3+2 pattern (tresillo), programmed as `X--X--X-`, creates an infectious, rolling groove that provides a powerful counterpoint to the straight 4/4 kick.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- Module 3 -->
            <section id="module3" class="py-16 md:py-24">
                <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-12">Module 3: Sound Design & Manipulation</h2>
                 <div class="space-y-12">
                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-xl text-white mb-4">Crafting Individual Drum Sounds</h3>
                        <ul class="list-disc list-outside space-y-3 text-gray-300 pl-5">
                            <li><strong>Sound Selection:</strong> Choosing the right core sounds is 80% of the battle. A good sound should feel at home *before* any processing.</li>
                            <li><strong>Sound Shaping:</strong> Go deep on parameters. <strong>Decay</strong> is your primary tool for controlling mix space. <strong>Tune</strong> drums to each other for a unified kit. Use <strong>attack/snappy</strong> to define a sound's transient.</li>
                            <li><strong>Gain Staging:</strong> A non-negotiable step. Set individual gains so that when all faders are at max, the master output hits a healthy level (-6dB to -3dB) without clipping.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-xl text-white mb-4">Applying Effects for Sonic Character</h3>
                        <ul class="list-disc list-outside space-y-3 text-gray-300 pl-5">
                            <li><strong>Distortion/Overdrive:</strong> Understand saturation (warmth) vs. aggressive overdrive (grit). Blending the "dry" and "wet" signals is key.</li>
                            <li><strong>Compression:</strong> A tool for shaping dynamics. Use a slow attack to make a snare punchier, or a fast attack on the bus to create a rhythmic "pumping" effect.</li>
                            <li><strong>Advanced Synthesis:</strong> Don't be intimidated by <strong>FM synthesis</strong>. It's how you create complex, inharmonic sounds like metallic clangs and bells. A "morph" control allows you to perform these timbral shifts in real-time.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- Module 4 -->
            <section id="module4" class="py-16 md:py-24">
                <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-12">Module 4: Performance Techniques</h2>
                 <div class="space-y-12">
                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-xl text-white mb-4">Interactive Pattern Creation</h3>
                        <ul class="list-disc list-outside space-y-3 text-gray-300 pl-5">
                           <li><strong>Step Sequencing vs. Real-Time Recording:</strong> Use both. Program a solid foundation with the step sequencer, then overdub organic, un-quantized percussion in real-time.</li>
                           <li><strong>Sub-Steps:</strong> Your microscope for rhythmic detail. Use it for incredibly fast 32nd or 64th note rolls (drags and ruffs) or glitchy hi-hat patterns.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-xl text-white mb-4">Building Dynamics with Variations and Fills</h3>
                        <ul class="list-disc list-outside space-y-3 text-gray-300 pl-5">
                            <li><strong>Pattern Variations:</strong> Think in terms of tension and release. Use A/B patterns to create a narrative arc.</li>
                            <li><strong>Fills & Rolls:</strong> A fill should signal a change. A simple 16th-note snare roll is a classic way to build anticipation.</li>
                            <li><strong>Mute Function:</strong> Arguably the most powerful performance tool. Mute the kick and bass for a dramatic breakdown, then drop them back in for immense perceived energy.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-xl text-white mb-4">Humanizing and Deconstructing the Beat</h3>
                        <ul class="list-disc list-outside space-y-3 text-gray-300 pl-5">
                            <li><strong>Shuffle (Swing):</strong> Delays every second 16th note for a "bouncing" feel. Apply it to hi-hats and shakers.</li>
                            <li><strong>Probability:</strong> Introduces controlled chaos. Set a snare to 50% probability to create unpredictable variations.</li>
                            <li><strong>Scatter/Beat Repeat:</strong> Use this like a spice. A short burst of a "stutter" effect can create a mind-bending transition.</li>
                            <li><strong>Motion Automation:</strong> Record parameter changes over time. Record a filter sweep on your hi-hats to have it play back automatically, freeing you up to tweak other things.</li>
                            <li><strong>Reload/Revert:</strong> Your safety net and creative tool. Mangle a pattern, build a chaotic crescendo, then hit "reload" to instantly snap back to the original for massive tension and release.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>
            
            <!-- Module 5 -->
            <section id="module5" class="py-16 md:py-24">
                <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-12">Module 5: Integration & Mixing</h2>
                <div class="space-y-12">
                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-xl text-white mb-4">Strategic Application of Effects</h3>
                        <ul class="list-disc list-outside space-y-3 text-gray-300 pl-5">
                            <li><strong>Reverb:</strong> Use <strong>pre-delay</strong> to preserve the clarity of the original sound before the reverb tail starts. Keep the kick drum dry.</li>
                            <li><strong>Delay:</strong> Use tempo-synced delays. A ping-pong delay adds width, and a filtered delay adds depth without clutter.</li>
                            <li><strong>Sidechain Compression:</strong> Beyond the classic kick/bassline, sidechain a synth pad to the kick to create a massive, pumping groove.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-xl text-white mb-4">External Integration and Signal Routing</h3>
                        <ul class="list-disc list-outside space-y-3 text-gray-300 pl-5">
                            <li><strong>Connectivity:</strong> Master MIDI and audio. Use your drum machine as the master clock for your whole setup.</li>
                            <li><strong>External Processing:</strong> Route an external synth through your drum machine's audio inputs to use its built-in effects.</li>
                            <li><strong>Trigger Outputs:</strong> Gold for modular users. Use a trigger pattern to drive a modular synth's sequencer for incredibly tight interplay.</li>
                            <li><strong>Mixing for the Club:</strong> Keep your most important elements—kick, snare, bass—panned to the center. Use stereo for "ear candy" but don't rely on it for core impact.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

        </div>
    </main>

    <!-- Footer -->
    <footer id="philosophy" class="bg-black py-16 md:py-24">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 md:px-8 text-center">
            <h3 class="text-xl text-white mb-4">Live Performance Workflow and Philosophy</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
                The focus in live techno is on hands-on control, creative limitation, and manipulating sounds in the moment. Many iconic tracks were created by processing the entire drum mix through a single gritty mixing desk. This highlights a philosophy that prioritizes performance and vibe over pristine, surgical separation. Embrace the idea of the drum machine as a whole instrument. Experimentation and a willingness to push sounds beyond their intended use are key to developing a unique sonic signature. True mastery is not knowing what every function does, but developing an intuitive, symbiotic relationship with your chosen machine.
            </p>
            <p class="text-xs text-gray-600 mt-12 tracking-widest">© 2025 TECHNO DRUM MACHINE THEORY</p>
        </div>
